825 nm. The integrated stroke emission energy in 50 nm increments from 430 to 850 nm decreases with increasing wavelength twice as fast as the decrease of solar energy over the same wavelength range.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}{\textless}p{\textgreater}Spectral emission data show that unresolved neutral nitrogen lines (NI) at 744.2 nm are more intense than the H-alpha emission at 656.3 nm. A flash with a continuing current shows strong emissions at 384.0 nm. These are identified as cyanogen (CN) emissions and appear to be a unique spectral signature of cloud-to-ground lightning flashes with continuing currents.{\textless}/p{\textgreater}{\textless}/section{\textgreater}},
